segments.text: from the Department of IBTE at Texas A&M University.

Today is October the 16th, and I am visiting with Dr. Don Clark, who has been at Texas A&M since 1967, has served as Professor of Industrial Vocational Technical Education, as well as Associate Dean for Research, and he will be sharing some insights and
thoughts about the College of Education as he has perceived it since he has been here in 1967 before it was even a College of Education formally.

And Dr. Clark, I would like to maybe just start with change because that's been the big thing since, well always, but in the College of Education I know you have experienced tremendous amounts of change and probably what I would like
for you to share is maybe what kind of impact these changes have had, whether they be political or sociological, on the growth and the development of the College of Education.
Well, maybe a place to start would be to talk about my arrival at Texas A&M University in 1967 and then evolve up a little bit through and then interrupt along the way.
When I came to Texas A&M University in 1967, we did not have a College of Education.
Frank Hubert was then the Dean of the College of Liberal Arts, and Fred Benson was the Dean of the College of Engineering.
And my appointment was in the College of Engineering, where the Department of Industrial Education resided.
Within that department, we had the program called Industrial Education.
a large percentage, 96% or more of the undergraduate students were in the industrial technology and industrial distribution programs.
So therefore, the emphasis was not on teacher education, but was rather on the technology program.
In the September of 1969 is when the College of Education became formalized as an administrative unit.
And what we really did was pull together
the teacher education programs from the three separate departments that existed at that time that had teacher education and created the College of Education.
What we really had was, prior to 69, we had teacher education in the College of Engineering through industrial education, in the College of Agriculture in the Department of Agriculture Education.
the Department of Education, which was in the College of Liberal Arts, along with the Department of Health and Physical Education, which was in the College of Liberal Arts.
So we really had teacher education residing in four departments in three separate colleges.
So it was under the leadership of Frank Hubert, who had great administrative insights, which we might want to discuss further, that pulled together the administrative unit of the College of Education

and pulled all teacher education elements then under one administrative umbrella with agriculture education answering in a joint relationship to the College of Agriculture and the College of Education, which they still exist.
So in 1969, when we created this College of Education,

There were those of us who were involved in the teacher education function in the old Department of Industrial Education came to the College of Education with James Boone coming in as the head of the Department of Industrial Education at that time, Les Hawkins, who has since retired, and myself.
There were as well as the faculty members who came to create the Department of Industrial Education within the College of Education.
We brought with us the undergraduate teacher education program
as well as the entire master's and doctoral level programs that were in existence.
The doctor of education, which we had in the best education, was the first doctorate in the field of education that was on this campus.
It preceded the development of the PhD in education by a number of years.
I don't have the specifics, but it was in place prior to the
The first doctorate, can you repeat that?
The first doctorate was in industrial?
In industrial education.
And that program preceded the one in the Department of Education.
That's the one that Dr. Barker was instrumental in putting together.
The education one.
The education doctorate.
Well, the one in the Department of Education.
Now, the one in the Department of Industrial Education, that was in the College of Engineering.
Right.
Dr. Barker was involved in that only to the degree of teaching courses and serving on committees.
And who was responsible for that one?
Within the College of Engineering, Dr. Chris Gronemann was the head of the department at the time that that doctoral program was started.

And then Dr. Everett Glaesner kind of came in and coordinated that program until Dr. Gronemann retired, which was in 1967, which actually made the faculty position available that I filled at a lower level.
Dr. Glaze may go on to the head of the department.
Now, when we created the College of Education, prior to that, there were four different departments in three separate colleges.
So then the old Department of Education was divided into three departments, being Educational Curriculum and Instruction, Educational Psychology, and Educational Administration.
It was quite a change when we pulled all teacher education together.
At the time we created the College of Education, I remember Frank Hubert introducing the faculty as the young faculty.
And remember that's 18 years ago.
And many of us who you're interviewing now, Glenn Johnson, Don Barker, various ones of us were younger then than we are now.
But it was really a privileged
be associated with the development and evolution of this new administrative unit, and the end of the dynamic leadership of Frank Hubert.

But as he introduced this, and as he put together the faculty for this college, we look at the type of people that have been attracted to it, especially in the earlier time of the, not to detract from those now, but the earlier time when that's Glenn Johnson coming from the

Ohio City University through Columbia, with Bob Schutz coming out of Stanford, with Hal Hawkins coming out of Harvard, with Jack Campbell is already here, but he's coming out of Columbia, coming to Teachers College of Columbia.
What attracted all these people to A&M?
Was it Dr. Hubert's
himself, or was it the opportunity to get in on something that was just really new and starting, or what do you think?

Well, I guess Lynn Johnson and I were here prior to the actual start of the college, so it was right at the time that Texas A&M, of course, was changing tremendously, and that we'd learned that there were such things as girls, and we were expanding, of course, it was interesting, I came here as a professor of college of engineering to

have very few girls in classes, but to talk to people like Paul Hensarling, who was in the Department of Education and realized that we had a kindergarten endorsement at Texas A&M as one of the first ones in the state, even though we were traditionally an all-male institution,
However, this kindergarten endorsement was primarily for summer school.
What was an endorsement?
Was that like something that they did?
Well, rather than a degree of being elementary education, your certification in elementary is, but to teach kindergarten, it was an endorsement on an existing certificate.
And so what we really had was a kindergarten endorsement so people would have their elementary certificates, and then they would get their kindergarten endorsement from us.
and many of those were summer school courses.
And those were for girls that were coming in, or late, or women?
Okay.
But it was interesting to be a traditionally male institution, one of the first kindergarten endorsements.
I think, of course, that was before there was a college to educate.
Right.
I don't know if you picked up any place in your discussion, Sylvie, about this man, Frank Hubert.
Not enough.
I would be dealing with him later on.
It was fun to hear a person who many, many people think about as a very...
structured, very, well, the word cold has been used to describe Frank Hubert, and I guess those of us who knew him better would say he was a very warm human individual.
In trying to build that a little bit, I'd like to share some personal things that I learned about working with him.
First, Frank Hubert got his original baccalaureate degree from the University of Texas and went to Orange in political science, and then went to Orange as band teacher.

And when he was in Orange, he tells a story about how he worked with the Bingo Bells, and the Bingo Bells was a drum and bugle corps in the mid-30s, which was kind of before the day of the drum and bugle corps for girls.
But he really worked for Ledger Stark, who was a lumberman in the area, a Stark family.
And he tells a story about performance-based teaching, performance-based employment.
I'll tell you a story.
song that Mr. Stark had heard over the radio, and he called Frank Hubert up and said, Frank, he said, I think we girls, he explained, he said, I'd like the girls to play that next week.
Hubert called the radio station and found out that the name of the song was, Hey, That's Boogie Woogie.
So this was right at the early Boogie Woogie time.
He ended up, Mr. Stark had told Hubert that there was $100 in it for him if the girls had that to play the following week.
So he
got the radio station, found out where it was, finally got a hold of a copy of the music, arranged it for all of the ranks that they had in their music corps, and they played it the following week.
He said, now that's performance based.
But he tells us stories of working with that group, taking them to Soldier's Field in Chicago on a train that was air conditioned back at that time, and how the girls
One girl had come from quite a lot of wealth in the Golden Triangle there of Beaumont, Orange area, where the other kids had come with brown paper sacks for their luggage for that trip.
Mr. Stark saw that and said, that'll never happen again.
So after that, when they traveled, each girl had their own piece of luggage with a companion overnight bag with all of the things that would go in it.
And each of them traveled in white coveralls.
And to hear Frank Hubert share this about wanting to meet the needs of economic deprived as well as economic well, gave me an insight into the man.
Also, his dad was a medical doctor, and as he talked about going to the homes of people of lesser means and

Frank talked about going to the homes of people with his dad for the delivery of children and so forth, and realizing the diversity in our population, the ethnic groups, and his dad was a doctor for all ethnic groups.
And at that time in Texas history, that says something about the heritage of Frank.
To finish off the Orange story, he went to Orange as a band teacher, then went back to

Austin during the summers worked on his masters and then stayed at Orange as principal of the high school and went into World War II and came out of World War II and went to UT and got his doctorate and then worked at the Texas Education Agency for a number of years prior to going back to superintendent of schools in Orange.
So all of his public school career was in Orange as first a teacher, then a principal, and then as a superintendent.
realizing that he replaced J.W.
Edgar when J.W.
Edgar went to the Texas Education Agency as Commissioner of Education.
That is when Frank Hubert went to Orange as superintendent of schools.
It was from that background, sharing all of that background with a man, he then came to Texas A&M University when there were four administrative units.
For clarity, let's call them colleges, but realize we were a Texas A&M college.
But now, if we take about Texas University, the equivalent of, and he came as the Dean of Arts and Sciences.
And you need to get him to talk about the evolution of all of this.
I'm sharing a lot about him, but trying to share some of his warmth.
So under his leadership, the College of Liberal Arts was divided into the College of Arts and the College of Science, or Liberal Arts and Science.
And out of Liberal Arts also came the College of Business Administration.
and now that also has been in the College of Education.
He deemed in the College of Arts and Sciences, then in the College of Middle Arts, and then in the College of Education.
So to deem in three separate colleges, but really he helped spawn those, which during a time of growth, he was a part of this growth here at Texas A&M University.
At the time he interviewed Jim Boone and myself for positions of leadership in the new college.
named Jim Boone, the head of the department in industrial ed.

He asked me if I would serve as the then coordinator of research and development for the college of education, which the following year was then elevated to the associate dean for research and development.
But his comment to us jokingly, but with sincerity, was, deans make mistakes.
But he held his finger up and waved and he says, but they only have to live with them for one year.
But then a twinkle in his eye that said, you know, I have faith in you, I have confidence in you, but this is not a tenured administrative position.
And of course I was pleased to be able to serve as his associate dean up until the time of his retirement and then moving on forward into the
working in the same position under the current dean.
And also under Dean Lindbacher, that one.
Under the interim dean.
Yes, under the interim dean of Dean Lindbacher.
And experiencing the administrative style of each of these three, I learned from each and gained professionally from each.
I guess the one that I wanted to almost put on tape was to try to dispel any feelings that Frank Hubert was that cold administrator who made dictatorial decisions for the dean's office.
Knowing him as I did, I feel he had great insights into the feeling for and of his faculty.
He had a pipeline into the faculty that many faculty members did not.
we're not aware of, I guess.
It was an informal one, but he had
great insights into their professional capabilities, their professional needs, as well as their personal needs and likes and dislikes.

Do you think that because it was a much smaller group at the time, it was easier to do that than it would be, say, now when the faculty has tripled probably, or I don't know how much it has grown since he was here, but

I'm hearing from other people that communication is okay, but it's strictly through the department head that there's not a whole lot of communication because it's just sometimes even within the one floor you don't know, you're not as able.
It can't help, size can't help but impact on it.
But there are those who could administer very large units and still have that feel for it.
I think he had that quality, that insightfulness that was needed to do that.

We didn't operate with a lot of formal committees, but yet there were appropriate committees, selected committees, and involvement of faculty in them, not to the degree that we have the committee structure in the university today.
We're operating with the Faculty Senate today, which in the
all of that speaks to more committee structure.
But he operated with a... That's all overall college, not just the College of Education.
That's the way it has to work now because of...
In the total university, it's more committee structure.
I see.
But even within the College of Education,
Our inquiry groups have certainly added some opportunities for faculty to feel a sense of input.
If they didn't feel it before, they have the opportunity to feel that now.
And perception is important.
Right.
Now, maybe that's something that I'm interested in finding out.
Was the goal of the mission, in your opinion, or the goal or mission of the college, which is right now teaching research and service, has it changed in the proportion or in how much it is
devoted to teaching or research now.
I'm trying to divide this study into the Hubert era as such, because that was the beginnings, and then the present era, and then look into the future a little bit, maybe.
But to what extent is that mission, do you feel, being fulfilled now versus how it was at the time?
Is the emphasis the same, I guess, is what I'm wanting to know.
The emphasis on teaching, I think, is not...
any different now than it was then.
I think we always must emphasize the teaching role in a university, and then use the
research and service role as support to teaching.
I realize that some colleges might look at it the other way around, but as a university, we have to look at it.
We do have a job of teaching, but then teaching is enhanced with appropriate research and service activities.
And I think that the emphasis on research is no different now than it was then.
There were more opportunities in my particular field of industrial vocational education.
There were more opportunities for research and service activities ten years ago than there are now because of the funding level.
Which I want to come back and speak to the development of the interdisciplinary education program which I was deeply involved.
And part of that was the result.
The reason that evolved as it has is because of external funding.
I think I would see our college grew in the earlier time because of external funding.
We can name various faculty members, or faculty member lines at least, and even incumbents in those lines, that are here today because of external funding that allowed us to develop programs.
And I don't see that happening today as much as I did then.
Let's just tick them off a little bit.
Community education was certainly one of the programs that evolved here because of major funding from the Mott Foundation.
Hal Hawkins was instrumental in getting some of those funds.
Bob Barrage was PMN as Director of the Center for Community Education and carried that role on for a number of years.
But it was through the funding from the Mott Foundation that the line position for the Bob Barrage Professor line was established in the Education Administration.
Well, that's a full tenure track line that someone else now carries, funded by the university.
And then as the funds for Mott Foundation diminished or were redirected, that position for him was there.
Taking other positions similar to that, when we created the Dr. Ponder, I believe him right now, he was the one who came in on soft money the first year he was here in health and physical education.
He came in on
There was funds from Baylor College of Medicine with the University of Houston to create a health administration program.
And we got funds from the Kellogg Foundation to Baylor College of Medicine back to the University of Houston, Texas University.
And it was through those funds that created this faculty position.
And when we created it, we were in a growth situation, in a tax situation here in Texas, where we could make these commitments that we can't make.
that we would, over a period of three years, absorb that position into the university budget.
So as the program generated student credit hours, then we were able to build a faculty position with that.

We can look at, in the industrial vocational education program, the position that Dr. Chris Borman originally came on was a soft money position under what we call the old EPDA, Professional Education and Professional Development Act, Section 553 funds.
These were, and they came through the state.
So we had state funds coming to Texas A&M to assist in the development of a vocational guidance program.
So when Dr. Borman came, he came as a professor, also wanting to help us develop a program in vocational guidance.
As his, the next year that he became a full-time professor, a budgeted line in the Department of Education and Psychology,
We retained that soft money for a couple of years, and I guess probably if we look at that position now, Jerry Capus is probably on that line, but has gone through four or five different people.
But that original line item came as soft money.
Soft money always refers to?
To contract and grant activity.
Okay.
As we look at additional funds, it was in the vocational education division.
We started our doctoral program in vocational education.
with 25 fully funded doctoral fellows.
I need to talk more about that era.
But that also created a couple line items for people.
We also created our adult education program through soft money.
And that created line item.
And then over time, evolved those into full tenure track positions.
So several of the positions that are in the college now as tenure track faculty members or tenure track lines are ones that started through, quote, soft money.
And of course, I was in such a.
I'd say almost an Indian position, that I was back on it now, of being the one that coordinated getting these dollars and assisting these programs in their early evolutionary stages.
It was a very rewarding period of time for me personally in doing this.
I'm glad Frank Hubert saw in me
to assist in doing that.
Let me just talk about the adult ed program, interdisciplinary education program a little bit and see how it has evolved, because it's unique in all university campuses.
Put it in the context of in 1969, when we created the College of Education, we had these six academic departments that we've already named.
In February of 1970, there was a man by the name of superintendent of schools
Dallas at the time.
Sorry, I'm dropping the name.
I'll have to pick that name back up.

It came on our campus and made a presentation to a group of graduate students and faculty members that by 1980, this is 1970 now, they would anticipate having more students enrolled in their adult and continuing education programs than they did at that time in their ongoing elementary and secondary programs.
Now you think about that, that's a very horrible statement.
So here I'd been appointed as a Associate Dean for Research and Development.
I was just a coordinator at that time.
I asked myself a question, what are we doing to prepare teachers to teach in that program?
So the first major proposal that exited the College of Education after I was here was a proposal to Texas Kidney Agency to develop an adult education program.
Now, so where within the
structure I just described to you of the six departments, would you put an adult education program?
It certainly is education psychology.
Adult psychology is different than adolescent psychology, child psychology.
It's certainly curriculum, but it's especially program administration.
So we, and there's some other place to put it.
The only adult education course we had on the books was on agriculture education.

About the same time, there's a program called, and I've already referenced it, the Education Professions Development Act, the EPDA, had money in it for development of graduate programs of vocational education, comprehensive vocational education.
So we had the Department of Agriculture Education and the Department of Industrial Education.
But vocational education is certainly more than those two.
So here we were to develop an administrative leadership program for vocational education.
So where would we place it in our administrative structure?
So what we did, we created a program called interdisciplinary education.
And in that interdisciplinary education, we housed these two programs.
One was considered to be a holding tank until they could do sprint off and do other things.
But the interdisciplinary really evolved around where we got the faculty from.
Here I was the coordinator in addition to my deans, subject deanship role, I was also a coordinator of interdisciplinary education.
And I would pull faculty from
each of the departments that needed, I needed to teach a course.
If I needed a course in guidance, I'd go to Ed Psych and get the person.
If I had a course in administration, vocational education, I'd go to industrial ed, I could go to ag ed.
We'd have, we'd go to EBCI while sitting and teach someone.
And we had all the flexibility to pull.
And one of the nice things about this, I don't feel I ever got the leftovers of the faculty.
I was able to always pull in the
The main faculty were to teach that course.
There was a good cooperative arrangement.
But there was a shortcoming.
Who was home to do the committee work?
The student advisors and so forth.

So finally we started putting some budget lines in that program, interdisciplinary education, to have a coordinator of adult education, a coordinator of adult extension, and a coordinator of vocational education.
Then we started putting additional monies in there.
So today, as we know the department now, it more or less operates as a department, even though it officially doesn't have departmental status.
It's an institutional education program.
It's not approved by the coordinating boards of the department.
But for all practical purposes, we operate as a department, because it has its own inventory of courses, its own category of faculty, its own category of students.
The members of that faculty are represented on our advisory committees in the college, on the policy committee.

all functions of all the unique it is not a department so it's just and the other unique thing about it though is that before we operate around here on the subvention of money earned from student credit hours generated if I in EDCI if Jack Campbell earns student credit hours those are credited back to EDCI if I earn
credit hours in industrial education, they're credited back to our department, industrial education.
However, if I teach a course in interdisciplinary education, like I teach my grads course, those student credit hours are IDED.
However, the subvention for those is credited back to the home department of where I have my academic appointment.
And that was something that, again, was one that we evolved through in the creation of this IDED program.

Another one, while I'm talking about the evolution of this adult education program, I was having coffee one Sunday morning with the then director of the Agriculture Extension Service, and he was somewhat bemoaning the fact that their extension personnel had a lot of good technical skills, but very few people skills.
They had a degree in animal science, but the first job they had was a 4-H director working with two-legged people, two-legged animals.
So I shared that with Frank Hubert Monday morning after I had gotten that from the director and we said why don't we add the word extension to that adult program.
And so with a stroke of the pen we changed the word from adult education to adult and extension education.
So our department, our adult ed program is adult and extension education, not by accident, but by planning that in, by coming

talking with people in agriculture extension that wanted this people skills and then having the dean allowing that to be put in and so now that is in the college of education rather than the college of agriculture and it was a John Hutchison who was then say the director of agriculture extension service and I evolved this plan and Don Seaman's appointment in interdisciplinary education when he came his appointment was

and really right up until almost last year was part-time in Ag College Extension Service and one of the secretaries in that program was funded by Ag College Extension Service all these years because we were wanting to prepare people to work in the Extension Service as well as the adult program.
So that has been a link or a connection with the Extension.
Is there anything that I can get where all of this is documented?
because, of course, I get it from the transcript, but is there something, some document that this would all be chronicled in?
Right.
I'm afraid that...
